<setup>

  <function name="f">tan(x)</function>
  <derivative name="fP">$f</derivative>

  <function name="T">sin(x)</function>
  <derivative name="TP">$T</derivative>

  <function name="B">cos(x)</function>
  <derivative name="BP">$B</derivative>

  <boolean name="correctQR">$bot=$B and $Dtop=$TP and $top=$T and $Dbot=$BP and $bot2=$B</boolean>
  <boolean name="correctFinal">$fPfinal=sec^2(x) or $fPfinal=(sec(x))^2 or $fPfinal=sec(x)^2</boolean>
  
</setup>

<p>
    Consider the function <m>f(x) = \tan(x)</m>, and remember that
    <m>\tan(x) = \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}</m>.

    <ol marker="a." >
      <li >
        <p >
          What is the domain of <m>f</m>?
            <p>
              <answer>
                <choiceInput>
                  <choice>All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \neq \dots \, , \, -\frac{\pi}{2}, \, -\frac{\pi}{4}, \, 0, \, \frac{\pi}{4}, \, \frac{\pi}{2}, \, ...</m></choice>

                  <choice credit="1">All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \neq \dots , \, -\frac{3\pi}{2}, \, -\frac{\pi}{2}, \, \frac{\pi}{2}, \, \frac{3\pi}{2}, \, ...</m></choice>

                  <choice>All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \neq \dots \, , \, -\pi, \, -\frac{\pi}{2}, \, 0, \, \frac{\pi}{2}, \, \pi, \, ...</m></choice>

                  <choice>All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \neq \dots \, , \, -2\pi, \, -\pi, \, 0, \, \pi, \, 2\pi, \, ...</m></choice>
                </choiceInput>
              </answer>
            </p>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Apply the quotient rule to <m>f(x) = \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}</m> in order to fill in the following blanks in the structure of <m>f'(x)</m> that results from the quotient rule:
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>f'(x) = (</m><answer name="bot"><award>$B</award></answer><m>\cdot</m><answer name="Dtop"><award>$TP</award></answer><m>-</m><answer name="top"><award>$T</award></answer><m>\cdot</m><answer name="Dbot"><award>$BP</award></answer><m>)/(</m> <answer name="bot2"><award>$B</award></answer><m>)^2</m>.
        </p>  

      </li>

      <li >
        <p >
          Recall that the Fundamental Trigonometric Identity states that
          <p>
            <me>
              \sin^2(x)+\cos^2(x)=1
            </me>
          </p>
          
        </p>
        <conditionalContent>
          <case condition="$correctQR = false">
            <p>
 
            </p>
          </case>
          <case condition="$correctQR = true">
            <p>
              Use the Fundamental Trigonometric Identity to generate a simpler form for <m>f'(x)</m> in the provided space below: 
            </p>
            <p>
              <m>
                f'(x) = \frac{\cos(x) \cos(x) + \sin(x) \sin(x)}{\cos^2(x)} = 
              </m> <mathInput name="dq_simp" minWidth="50" prefill="/(cos(x))^2"></mathInput>
      <answer symbolicEquality><award><when>$dq_simp = 
        (1)/(cos(x))^2
      </when></award></answer>
            </p>
         </case>
<!--
<answer name= "PA_2-3-1_ans2" matchPartial symbolicEquality><award> <when> $expandedp=2t^5+8t^3 or $expandedp=8t^3+2t^5 </when></award> </answer>
-->          
      </conditionalContent>         
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Recall that <m>\sec(x) = \frac{1}{\cos(x)}</m>.
          How can we now express <m>f'(x)</m> in an even simpler way in terms of the secant function?
          <p>
            <m>
              f'(x) = 
            </m>
            <mathInput name="fPfinal" />
            <answer name="fPsimplest" symbolicEquality>
              <award><when>$fPfinal=sec^2(x) or $fPfinal=(sec(x))^2 or $fPfinal=sec(x)^2</when></award>
            </answer>
          </p>
          <conditionalContent>
          <case condition="$correctFinal= false">
            <p>
 
            </p>
          </case>
          <case condition="$correctFinal = true">
            <p>
              You've now correctly found the simplest form of the derivative of the tangent function:
              <me>
                \frac{d}{dx}[\tan(x)] = \sec^2(x).
              </me>  
            </p>
         </case>         
      </conditionalContent> 
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          For what values of <m>x</m> is <m>f'(x)</m> defined?
            <p>
              <answer>
                <choiceInput>
                  <choice>All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \neq \dots \, , \, -\frac{\pi}{2}, \, -\frac{\pi}{4}, \, 0, \, \frac{\pi}{4}, \, \frac{\pi}{2}, \, ...</m></choice>

                  <choice credit="1">All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \neq \dots , \, -\frac{3\pi}{2}, \, -\frac{\pi}{2}, \, \frac{\pi}{2}, \, \frac{3\pi}{2}, \, ...</m></choice>

                  <choice>All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \neq \dots \, , \, -\pi, \, -\frac{\pi}{2}, \, 0, \, \frac{\pi}{2}, \, \pi, \, ...</m></choice>

                  <choice>All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \neq \dots \, , \, -2\pi, \, -\pi, \, 0, \, \pi, \, 2\pi, \, ...</m></choice>
                </choiceInput>
              </answer>
            </p>
          In particular, we notice that the domain of <m>f'(x)</m> is <answer>
                <choiceInput inline>
                  <choice>?</choice>
                  <choice>different from</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">the same as</choice>
                  <choice>unrelated to</choice>
                </choiceInput>
              </answer> the domain of <m>f</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>